Wash and dry all produce. Preheat the oven to 450 degrees. Cut the @Yukon Gold Potatoes{24%ounce} into 1⁄4-inch wedges. Peel and cut the @Carrots{4%piece} into 1⁄2 inch coins. Strip half the @Thyme{½%ounce} leaves off the sprigs; set the remaining sprigs aside.

Toss the potatoes and carrots on separate #baking sheets{}, each with a large drizzle of @Olive Oil{2%tablespoon} and a pinch of @Salt{} and @Pepper{}. Toss the potatoes with the thyme leaves and the carrots with a pinch of @Chili Flakes{1%teaspoon} (feel free to leave them off for the kids). Place both sheets in the oven for ~{20-25%minutes}, tossing halfway through cooking until golden brown.

Heat a large drizzle of olive oil in a large #oven-proof pan{} over medium-high heat. Pat dry the @Airline Chicken Breasts{24%ounce} with a #paper towel{}. Season the chicken breasts on all sides with salt and pepper. Add the chicken to the #pan{}, skin-side down, and cook for ~{6-8%minutes}, reducing the heat if necessary, until golden brown and crispy. Flip over and place the chicken onto the #baking sheet{} with the carrots. Finish cooking in the oven for ~{7-10%minutes}, or until the juices run clear when pierced with a knife. Set aside to rest for about ~{5%minutes}.

While the chicken cooks, halve, peel, and thinly slice the @Shallot{2%unit}. Cut the @Lemon{1%unit} into wedges.

Heat the same pan you used for the chicken over medium-high heat. Add the shallot and a small pinch of chili flakes (if desired) to the pan and cook, tossing for ~{2-3%minutes}, until soft. Add @water{1%cup} and the @Chicken Stock Concentrate{2%unit}(s), scraping up any browned bits from the bottom of the pan. Bring to a simmer, then add the thyme sprigs and @Apricot Jam{2%tablespoon}; stir to thoroughly combine. Simmer until thickened to a glaze consistency, for about ~{3-4%minutes}. Taste and season with salt, pepper, and the juice of two lemon wedges.

> TIP: If you want your glaze spicier, add more chili flakes!

Serve the apricot-glazed chicken on a bed of thyme-roasted potatoes and carrots, then drizzle with the apricot glaze. Serve with a wedge of lemon and enjoy!